The anti-China tech war in the United States.
NEW YORK – The worst foreign-policy mistake made by Americans (and their allies) in the last generation – indeed, in several generations – was the 2003 “war of choice” launched on Iraq, which purported to eliminate – and actually did not have – weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity of understanding the erroneous logic behind this disastrous decision has become more urgent than ever, as the same logic is being invoked to defend similarly misleading US policies today.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that we should act as if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands was certain (even if it were small, like 1 percent).
But this mode of reasoning almost always leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the U.S. government's说法, since we cannot assure the safety of Chinese technology, we should address and ban it by defining it as inherently harmful.
The correct decision applies probability estimates to various alternative courses of action.
A generation ago, U.S. policymakers should have considered not just the (claimed) 1% risk of mass destructive weapons falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of going to war based on multiple flawed premises.
By simply focusing on that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention away from the fact that the war in Iraq was actually unjustified and would severely destabilize both the Middle East and global politics.
The problem with Cheneyism is not just that it acts on minimal risks without considering the vastly higher potential costs, but that politicians always stoke fear for some unstated purpose.
This is what American leaders are doing again: stirring up fear about Chinese tech companies by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks.
The case that is most relevant (but not the only one) is the U.S. government's attack on the telecommunications technology company Huawei.
The United States is gradually closing off its domestic market to the company and is working to strangle its global operations.
Like Iraq, the United States may ultimately cause a geopolitically senseless disaster without any justification.
I have worked in developing countries and have always been following Huawei's technological advancements because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant momentum for poverty alleviation and the realization of other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encourage the industry to enhance its actions towards achieving the sustainable development goals.
I had written a brief preface (unremunerated) for a report that Huawei had prepared on this topic, and as a result, I was criticized by those hostile to China. In response, I consulted industry executives and government officials to ask if there was any evidence of Huawei's misconduct, and the repeated answer I received was that Huawei's conduct is no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment could compromise global security.
American officials claim that "backdoors" in Huawei's software or hardware could allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance on a global scale.
They note that Chinese law requires Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are now before us.
Huawei's 5G equipment offers affordable prices with excellent quality and currently leads many competitors, and it has already begun to be promoted.
Its high performance stems from substantial investments in research and development over many years, economies of scale, and navigating the Chinese digital market.
Given the importance of this technology for their sustainable development, it would be unwise for low-income economies around the world to refuse to roll out 5G early.
However, despite not having any evidence of backdoors, the US is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The United States' claim is universal.
As a U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner put it: "The country that has 5G will have the related innovations and set the standards for the rest of the world – and that country is unlikely to be the United States at present."
Other countries – especially the UK – have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if vulnerabilities were discovered in the future, they would likely be patchable at that point.
The debate over Huawei is also raging in Germany, where the U.S. government has threatened to reduce intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei’s 5G technology out.
Perhaps pressured by the United States, the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement akin to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not an area where a group that cannot be fully trusted should be allowed to tread."
And he was unable to present any evidence of specific crimes.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel was working behind the scenes to open the market for Huawei.
But ironically, America’s complaints actually reflect in part its own surveillance activities at home and abroad – though this is hardly newsworthy.
Chinese equipment may make it harder for the U.S. government to implement secret surveillance.
But any government's unlawful surveillance should be halted.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should be part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should opt for diplomacy and institutional guarantees, rather than engage in a technological war.
The threatening impact of America's demand to blacklist Huawei extends not only to the early rollout of 5G networks but also poses a significant risk to rule-based trading systems.
The United States is no longer the global uncontested technological leader, and neither President Trump nor his advisors wanted to compete within a rules-based framework.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They are also attempting to undermine the World Trade Organization’s dispute resolution mechanism by paralyzing it, which similarly reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration is able to "successfully" divide the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts will multiply.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade not only to enhance global efficiency and expand the market for American technologies but also to reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
Part of the reason for the collapse was the US protectionist tariff imposed under the 1930 Smoot-Holley Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression and contributed to Hitler's rise, ultimately pushing the world towards the outbreak of World War II.
As in other fields, stoking fear in international affairs in order to take action – rather than acting on the evidence – is a path to destruction.
Let us uphold rationality, evidence, and rules; this is the safest approach.
Let us establish an independent monitoring body to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on other countries or launch cyber wars.
In this way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
